bāhya, cf. bāhy-ābhyantar-ādāya (IE 8-5;<BR>Ep. Ind., Vol. <BR>XVI, p. 276, text line 14);<BR>‘income from the sale of things <BR>imported in a village’, same as Tamil puṟav-āyam (SITI), <BR>‘revenue from external sources (collected mainly in cash)’ or <BR>Tamil puṟa-kaḍamai (SITI), ‘external taxes’, explained as <BR>taxes and fees payable to the State. But puṟa-kaḍamai is the <BR>same as puṟav-āyam. Bāhya and ābhyantatra may thus mean <BR>respectively taxes payable to the king and those payable to <BR>the village authorities. See ābhyantara. Cf. samudaya-bāhy- <BR>ādya-stamba (EI 23), ‘land covered with original shrubs, <BR>i. e. waste which does not yield any revenue to the State’. <BR>(HD), a class of royal servants distinguished from <BR>Antaraṅga. See Rājataraṅgiṇī, VIII. 426, 680, 1542.

